# What She Can Do

SkyDexia is a build-and-ship workspace that helps a person go from idea to working product without needing to know every technical step ahead of time.

## In plain language

SkyDexia can:

- hold your project in one place
- let you bring in a folder, a ZIP, or a saved workspace source
- save your work as a real workspace snapshot
- let AI help edit and build that workspace
- run commands for the project like install, build, test, and start
- show terminal output so you can see what happened
- start app runtimes and stop or restart them
- track ports and expected environment keys for the project
- save reusable workbench setups so a project can be reopened the same way later
- create starter project structures from templates
- push the same saved workspace to SkyeDrive, GitHub, and Netlify
- keep release actions honest by recording deferred actions when outside credentials are missing
- replay those deferred release actions later when credentials are available

## What that means for a normal person

If you are not technical, SkyDexia is supposed to act more like a product factory than a raw code editor.

You can think of her like this:

- the workspace is your product folder
- the AI lane is your builder/helper
- the runtime is the machine that actually runs your app
- the terminal is the proof screen that shows what the machine did
- SkyeDrive is your saved workspace backup lane
- GitHub is your code shipping lane
- Netlify is your website publishing lane

## End-to-end flow

This is the basic full journey SkyDexia already supports.

### 1. Get into the workspace

You unlock the app with the founder or session gate.

Once inside, SkyDexia gives you a real working workspace instead of a fake demo buffer.

### 2. Bring in a product idea or existing files

You can start in a few ways:

- open a saved workspace
- open a SkyeDrive source
- drag in a folder
- drag in a ZIP
- use a bootstrap template to create a starter app

This means you can either continue old work or start something new fast.

### 3. Set up how the project should run

SkyDexia can read or save a workbench profile so the project remembers things like:

- what command starts it
- what command builds it
- what port it uses
- what env keys it expects
- what common tasks should be available

She also has runtime presets for common project shapes so you do not have to type everything from scratch.

### 4. Let AI help build the product

You can give SkyDexia a prompt and have the AI lane work on the project through the secured server path.

In simple terms, that means:

- you describe what you want
- the AI works on the actual workspace
- the same workspace can then be saved, run, and shipped

This is important because the AI work is connected to the real project lane, not some disconnected chat toy.

### 5. Run commands and tasks

SkyDexia has a workbench area where you can:

- run custom terminal commands
- run saved task presets
- review terminal transcripts
- stop running tasks
- reopen task URLs when a preview server comes up

This is the part that makes her act more like a real online dev environment and less like a simple text editor.

### 6. Start the product runtime

SkyDexia can materialize a runtime, start it, check if it is alive, read logs, restart it, and stop it.

In normal terms:

- she can try to bring your app to life
- tell you whether it actually started
- show you the logs if something breaks
- stop it cleanly when you are done

### 7. Show the important project details

SkyDexia can surface things people usually lose track of, including:

- current runtime mode
- task sessions
- terminal output
- known ports
- expected env keys
- release queue and history
- storage backend status

That helps a beginner understand what is going on without digging through hidden files.

### 8. Save the workspace properly

When you save, SkyDexia writes the workspace snapshot through the package lane.

That matters because other actions can use the same saved state.

So instead of having one version in the editor and a different version in deploy, she tries to keep those actions aligned.

### 9. Back up or restore with SkyeDrive

SkyDexia can save the workspace into SkyeDrive-style records and reopen those records later.

That gives you:

- restore points
- source continuity
- rollback help
- another recovery path besides GitHub

### 10. Connect release lanes

SkyDexia can connect to:

- GitHub for code push
- Netlify for deploy

If tokens are available, she can do the real action.

If tokens are missing, she does not lie about it. She records a deferred release entry so you can come back and replay it later.

That is a big deal because fake success is worse than an honest queue.

### 11. Publish and replay later if needed

If GitHub or Netlify are not ready yet, SkyDexia can keep the release intent in the queue.

Later, once the credentials exist, you can replay the action.

So the work is not lost just because the final shipping credential was missing at that exact moment.

## What she is especially good at right now

SkyDexia is already strong at:

- keeping one real workspace state across edit, run, save, and release
- helping structure projects with templates and presets
- giving AI a real package lane to work through
- giving beginners visible controls instead of hidden terminal-only workflows
- preserving release truth instead of pretending GitHub or Netlify already worked
- making hosted and self-hosted runtime lanes behave like real owned product infrastructure

## What a non-technical user can realistically do with her

A non-technical user can use SkyDexia to:

- start a product from a template
- ask AI to create or change the product
- run the app
- inspect the output
- save versions
- restore versions
- connect a release target
- publish when credentials are ready

That does not magically remove every hard product decision, but it does collapse a lot of the painful setup and shipping steps into one place.

## What makes her different from a normal editor

A normal editor mostly lets you type files.

SkyDexia also tries to manage the full lane around those files:

- workspace state
- runtime start and stop
- task execution
- terminal history
- project presets
- starter templates
- backup and restore
- AI tasking
- release queue and replay
- hosted durability

That is why she can function more like a product-operating environment instead of just a code box.

## The simple promise

The simple promise of SkyDexia is this:

Give her an idea, a project folder, or a starter template, and she can help you shape it, run it, save it, back it up, and push it toward a real shipped product from one connected lane.

## The beginner version in one sentence

SkyDexia is a workspace girl who helps you build, run, save, back up, and ship a product from one place, with AI, task running, runtime control, and real release lanes all tied to the same project state.